## 1. SERP Intent Analysis

### 1a. Dominant Content Format

The Redfin result (and the broader SERP for this keyword) is dominated by **interactive listing/directory pages**: geo-targeted apartment listings with filters, maps, photos, and price data. These are transactional product pages, not editorial articles.

brightplace cannot and should not replicate a real-time listing directory. The strategic play is to produce the **informational article that sits above or alongside the directory pages in AI-generated answers and featured snippets**, answering the practical questions renters have when they search this term: what should I be paying, what do I look for, how do I evaluate what I find. This is the content gap the big ILS players leave open. Their pages show listings but offer no guidance framework.

**Content format for this article:** A utility-first how-to framework article with a comparison table and FAQ section. This format targets the "how do I find and evaluate a 1BR near me" layer of intent that listing pages cannot satisfy.

### 1b. Content Depth Benchmark

The competitor (Redfin) provides near-zero editorial content: a title, one subtitle, and a listing grid. There is no prose, no guidance, no data framework. The PAA questions and Claude's response (Data Source 3) confirm that searchers have dense practical questions: affordability thresholds, price benchmarks by market, credit requirements, evaluation criteria.

**Target word count: 1,100-1,300 words.** Long enough to answer the questions the listing pages ignore. Short enough to stay within the /knowledgebase/ format spec and maintain reading momentum.

